snippet.textDisplay: I am going through the exact same thing as you and I wish I could just fly to New Jersey and give you guys a big hug but I live all the way in Australia. Last year January 19th I lost my mum to cancer. First she had breast cancer, brain cancer and then it moved into her back and into her blood (leukaemia). It was a really tough time for me and felt hopeless. I never wanted to cry because it made me feel weak and I also avoided looking at old photos and stuff so I wouldn't. I never thought this type of thing would happen to our family. When my mum sat us all down at the table and said she only had 1 year to live I had a wave of anxiety rush over me. I had been living in complete fear for 3 years and that really hit me like a bus. 5 days later the time halved and every day it just got shorter and shorter to the point that it got from 1 year to 3 days over the span of a month. One day I came home from gymnastics and all my Italian relatives were there and them and my dad sat me and my brother down at the table. I will never forget my brother saying "No don't tell me it happened" and my dad whispering under his breath "yes". That was the most tragic day of my life. Just thought I would share my story with you guys because I feel like we went through very similar things. I will be donating $250 to your foundation to support cancer foundations to stop this stupid disease. Ethans haircut looks great by the way. ily❤️❤️

snippet.textDisplay:
To the bravest people out there, to Gray to Ethan and to everyone who’s grieving the loss of a loved one, words will never be enough to describe how strong and how brave you are for holding on, I don’t even know how to begin cause i’ve never been in that place but i’ve always thought about it since i was a kid, and it has always haunted me without it even happening, no matter what i say and no matter how much i try words will never be enough to describe half of what you’re going through...
And you know how they say you’ll never get over the loss of a loved one but you’ll just get used to the feeling.
everyone who has gone through this has lost them in different ways, or maybe some of you who are reading this have gone through the same exact thing, and everyone’s grief is different, but all humans are connected through pain right? Some are going through more than the others and some are not even with us this day.. but we’re all feeling the same emotion which is pain..
You’re not alone.
And grieving is okay, crying is okay, missing them is okay, don’t isolate yourself, you’re a human being and emotions are part of being human, it’s normal.
It’s hard to think about it and living with it is even harder, but you can, trust me you do, no matter how old you are or who you’ve lost, you can, you know why? Cause you’re strong, cause you’re brave. I promise it’ll get easier cause you’ll know how to cope with it over time.
And don’t say if they were here they wouldn’t wanna see me this way, or they wouldn’t wanna see me cry...
Remember if they were here they wouldn’t wanna see you concealing your emotions, cause they know it’s not good for you, don’t restrain yourself cause you’re a human being, and it’s okay to have fun cause that’s what they want you to do, don’t be hard on yourself. We’re all with you and we will be with you every step of the way praying that someday soon it’ll get easier. I love you. We love you.❤️❤️❤️

snippet.textDisplay:
Thanks for making this you two.. I lost my dad 2 years ago on January 2nd. I remember the day of that first year came and went. Since it was around the holidays, they aren't the same.. We didn't know it was coming. Just one day.. he was gone. Everything I knew and had of my own was just gone; my house cause of the fire, all of my personal possessions inside of it, my car [which was like a child to me], and my dad.. was just gone. I literally lost everything but the clothes on my back. But the finality of it all.. my house, my home, my dad.. was just gone. My dad literally did EVERYTHING for my sister and I. He came from Italy, with no money, barely speaking English, but he built a construction company, from the ground up. He worked almost every single day, so hard, never complaining of why he did. He did that for us, to make sure my sister and I would be okay when he was gone. Even 2 years later, the reality of it all hasn't completely hit me yet. There are still days I don't believe that he isn't just a phone call away, a knock at his door, with a warm meal and a roof to put over my head. For a while, I'd almost call him. I never realized how much I ran to him for everything. He literally lived his life to protect and keep us safe..

You guys made me realize it is okay and it does help to go see someone to talk to about it and I'm making an appointment with a doctor the moment I'm finished with this. Watching you two mirrors my sister and I, after he passed, so closely, so seriously, thank you for sharing this. Hearing all the stories from all the people whos lives your father has touched, reminded me of all the stories I heard, and am still hearing, of my father and it brought a much needed smile to my face.

So, thank you two, truly, from the bottom of my heart.

_Felicia Terribile
[Instagram: EnzoFelipe]

Oh, and hopefully I can pass something over you guys,that I've learned that I hope will help. Losing a parent, someone who is and always was one of the closest people, if not the most close person to you in your life, is such an odd and hard to describe feeling that unfortunately never goes away. To me it felt like someone signed me up for a club I never knew existed and no one ever really knows the right way to tell u how to navigate your way through it all. HOWEVER, those nights when you're lying in bed and your mind
ruthlessly will not let you sleep because it will not shut up or stop going in circles, do eventually start to happen less often. You find them happening fewer and farther in between. When you find that odd feeling of losing your parent start to creep up in you, with time, it start to morph some of the pain into a sense of sort of happiness. Thinking of your father will still hurt, but you'll start thinking of more positive and happy memories. You'll still have the 'What if..'s and the 'Why..'s but with them will come with a 'Remember when.." and a smile. Like I said, that 'Club I Never Knew Existed' feeling never leaves you, but it does get better, and with it, sleep comes easier too.

snippet.textDisplay: I cried thinking of my dad...how he was my everything. How the only thing my dad didn’t teach me was how to live without my best friend in this entire world. Everyone says my dad held onto his life as long as he could only because he needed to know I would be okay/taken care of. It took four months from diagnosis after a random visit to the hospital for stomach/lower back pain to sitting around my dad in his final moments at hospice. My dad had stage 4 cancer in his pancreas, liver, and lungs but up until a week before that first hospital visit my dad worked his manual labor carpentry job 8am-5pm without fail, he was an incredibly strong-willed person. He was the greatest man I have ever known. I guess I just wanted to share a snippet of who my dad was so he could never be forgotten. Thank you for making this documentary it really encouraged me to take care of myself and feel things I guess I kept deep down.  I’m proud of you both for posting this, and I know your dad would be too ❤️
